 Hermes," emerged from the amalgamation of the wisdom gods Hermes and Thoth and is one of the most enigmatic figures of intellectual history. Since antiquity, the legendary "wise Egyptian" has been considered the creator of several mystical and magical writings on such topics as alchemy, astrology, medicine, and the transcendence of God. Philosophers of the Renaissance celebrated Hermes Trismegistus as the founder of philosophy, Freemasons called him their forefather, and Enlightenment thinkers championed religious tolerance in his name. To this day, Hermes Trismegistus is one of the central figures of the occult—his name is synonymous with the esoteric.In this scholarly yet accessible introduction to the history of Hermeticism and its mythical founder, Florian Ebeling provides a concise overview of the Corpus Hermeticum and other writings attributed to Hermes. He traces the impact of Christian and Muslim versions of the figure in medieval Europe, the power of Hermeticism and Paracelsian belief in Renaissance thought, the relationship to Pietism and to Freemasonry in early modern Europe, and the relationship to esotericism and semiotics in the modern world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aHermetismxHistory. 4aConsumer Health & Fitness. 4aHistory. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aHistory of scholarship on the Hermetica.  aMarsilio Ficino.  aalchemy.  aalkemy.  aancient religion.  aancient religious studies.  aancient theology.  aarab hermeticism.  achristian hermeticism.  acorupus hermeticum.  acosmology.  aegyptian god thoth.  aegyptian hermes trismegistus.  aegyptian sage.  aegyptology.  aesoteric hermeticism.  aestoterica.  agreek god hermes.  ahellenism.  ahellenistic egypt.  ahermes astrologer.  ahermes philosophy. 